<Layout title="Le-Kit's Terms and Conditions">
  <main style="max-width: 900px; margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem;">
    <h1>Terms and Conditions</h1>

    <p>Last updated: March 31, 2026</p>

    <p>
      Le-Kit is an open source project in active development. Things may change, break, be incomplete, or behave
      differently than expected.
    </p>

    <h2 id="work-in-progress">Work in Progress</h2>
    <p>This project is experimental. APIs, styles, and behavior can change without notice while the project evolves.</p>

    <h2 id="as-is">Provided "As Is"</h2>
    <p>
      The software, documentation, and examples are provided "as is", without warranties of any kind, express or
      implied, including merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, and non-infringement.
    </p>

    <h2 id="liability">Limitation of Liability</h2>
    <p>
      By using this project, you agree that the maintainers and contributors are not liable for any direct, indirect,
      incidental, special, consequential, or other damages resulting from use of the software or inability to use it.
    </p>

    <h2 id="your-responsibility">Your Responsibility</h2>
    <p>
      You are responsible for evaluating, testing, and validating Le-Kit in your own environment before using it in
      production or business-critical systems.
    </p>

    <h2 id="support">Support Expectations</h2>
    <p>There is no guaranteed SLA, support contract, or response time. If something is not working, you can:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Open an issue on GitHub with reproduction steps.</li>
      <li>Submit a fix via pull request.</li>
      <li>Fork the project and adapt it for your use case.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="license">License</h2>
    <p>
      Use of this project is governed by the repository license (currently MIT). In case of conflict, the license text
      in the repository is the source of truth.
    </p>

    <h2 id="changes">Changes to These Terms</h2>
    <p>
      These terms may be updated over time as the project matures. Continued use of the project means you accept the
      latest version.
    </p>
  </main>
</Layout>
